  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering carries serious criminal penalties. Generally, individuals convicted of money laundering can face:\n\n1. Significant criminal penalties:\n- Potential prison sentences of up to 10-20 years\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Criminal forfeiture of assets\n\n2. Potential additional consequences:\n- Asset seizure\n- Restitution payments\n- Probation\n- Loss of professional licenses\n\n3. Specific penalties depend on:\n- Amount of money involved\n- Specific circumstances of the offense\n- Whether it's a first or repeat offense\n- Connection to other criminal activities\n\n4. Legal statutes covering money laundering:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money laundering crimes)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Monetary transactions in criminally derived property)\n\nThe precise penalties can vary based on specific case details and prosecutorial discretion. Anyone facing potential money laundering charges should consult a qualified criminal defense attorney for specific legal guidance.",
